## 4. Psychological and Social Dimensions

### Emotional Burden and Mental Health

The psychological impact of climate change extends beyond anxiety to include feelings of grief, despair, anger, and shame. These emotions are compounded by perceptions of inadequate governmental action, leading to what some researchers term "moral injury" among youth ([BPS Research Digest, 2021](https://digest.bps.org.uk/2021/10/29/young-people-around-the-world-report-high-levels-of-climate-anxiety/)).

The mental health implications are significant, with climate anxiety contributing to stress and impairing daily functioning for a substantial portion of young people globally ([Nature, 2021](https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-021-02582-8)).

### Coping and Hope

Despite the prevalence of negative emotions, some young people also express hope and optimism, though these positive feelings are less common. Psychologists emphasize the importance of fostering hope and agency through effective climate policies and communication to mitigate the mental health burden ([JSTOR Daily, 2021](https://daily.jstor.org/coping-with-climate-anxiety/)).

---

## 5. Summary and Opinion

The evidence from multiple high-quality sources paints a clear picture: global concern about climate change is widespread and intensifying, with particularly acute emotional and psychological impacts on young people. The pervasive feelings of worry, fear, and helplessness are closely linked to perceptions of insufficient government action, which many young people interpret as a betrayal.

Public expectations for government leadership on climate change are high and growing, yet satisfaction with governmental responses remains relatively low. This gap between expectation and perceived performance contributes to climate anxiety and undermines public trust.

Given these findings, it is imperative that governments not only implement ambitious climate policies but also communicate transparently and empathetically with their citizens, particularly youth, to address both the environmental and psychological dimensions of the crisis. Failure to do so risks exacerbating mental health challenges and social unrest.

